answers.body_markdown:
With the await syntax available now for Node in Lambda, you can make some changes that better fit that style. For example you no longer need a callback and you can directly return the response object. This may solve your problem:

```javascript
export const hello: Handler = async (event: APIGatewayEvent, context: Context) =&gt; {

  // External Http call with Axios
  let URL:string = &quot;https://demo8946897.mockable.io&quot;;
  let mockResponse = await axios.get(URL,{});

  // Send response
  return {
    statusCode: 200,
    body: JSON.stringify({
      message: &#39;Go Serverless Webpack (Typescript) v1.0! Your function executed successfully!&#39;,
      mockResponse: mockResponse.data
    }),
  };
}
```

The solution was to wrap the response body with `JSON.stringify`. The response body *must* be a string. I had nested objects in my axios result that I was including in my function response as `mockResponse`.

```
export const hello: Handler = async (event: APIGatewayEvent, context: Context) =&gt; {

  // External Http call with Axios
  let URL:string = &quot;https://demo8946897.mockable.io&quot;;
  let mockResponse = await axios.get(URL,{});

  // Send response
  return {
    statusCode: 200,
    body: JSON.stringify({
      message: &#39;Go Serverless Webpack (Typescript) v1.0! Your function executed successfully!&#39;,
      mockResponse: mockResponse.data
    })
  };
}
```

